promptness of\nthe Treasury officials and the\nurgency of our financiers, mer\nchants, and bankers the close\nof 1007 will witness as great an\nincrease of our money volume\nin four months as came in three\nyears after the panics of 1873\nand 1803.\n\"Money is death to the financial\npanic, and the remedy is at hand\nand being applied.\nEurope gives us $75,000,000 in\ngold in thirty days' time, and,\nafter giving us that great sum,\nby January 1, 1008 we will have\nmore gold on hand than Europe\npossessed July 1, 1907. That\n$75,000,000 only repsesents the\nnew gold that Africa has pro-\ni duced in six months' time, and\nEurope has at her command as\nan iucrease of her July 1, stock\nthe production of Australia and\nIndia. Our own gold mines are\nproducing daily and their pro\nduct is nearly three times the\namount it was in 1W3. We keep\nall our new gold, we reinforce\nit with the source of millions\nfrom abroad, and are ready to\nback that ail up with new bank\ncirculation to any extent requir\ned. The congress that convenes\nwill quickly respond to the call\nof the President and the country.\nThe Post is willing to go on\nrecord wit n the prediction that\nby next April or May tho pros\nperity of the country will be in\nfull swing again, sustained by\nample supply of money and un\nbounded confidence in the future.\nThe flower Safety has been\nplucked from the nettle Danger.\nThe banks and trust companies\nof \"Wa-dnngton, solvent and se\ncure, have given splendid ex\nample to the country of safe and\nsound banking.' They are free\nfrom speculation, spoliation and\n.seltishncss.\nThey have carried the fortunes\nof the community with safety to\ndepositors and with credit and\nhonor to themselves. Tho days\nof doubt are over and the imme\ndiate future is very encouraging.\nWashington Post.\nnyOU can see what's coming; and you don't have to guess\nLi)\nM W\"\",r' v f i t .H\nfte efs a bigger profit, and cause for Thanksgiving that will last a good deal longer\nhe'll e